# GitHub Secrets Configuration Template
# Copy this file to github-secrets.txt and fill in your actual values
# Add these secrets to your GitHub repository:
# Go to Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=AKIA_YOUR_ACCESS_KEY_HERE
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_access_key_here
AWS_REGION=us-east-1
EC2_INSTANCE_ID=i-1234567890abcdef0
S3_DEPLOYMENT_BUCKET=production-agent-deployments-123456789
ENVIRONMENT=production

# Additional Information:
# - AWS Account ID: 123456789012
# - Instance Public IP: 1.2.3.4
# - Load Balancer DNS: your-alb-dns-name.elb.amazonaws.com
# - Application URL: http://your-instance-ip
# - API Documentation: http://your-instance-ip/docs

# Instructions:
# 1. Create an IAM user for GitHub Actions with the policy in DEPLOYMENT_GUIDE.md
# 2. Replace the placeholder values above with your actual values
# 3. Add these secrets to your GitHub repository
# 4. Push your code to trigger the first deployment
# 5. Test the deployment using the provided URLs

# Security Note:
# Never commit the actual github-secrets.txt file to version control
# This template file is safe to commit as it contains no real credentials
